  "prompt": "Why did the government of India introduced a 2000 rupee note instead of a new 1000 rupee note?",
  "response": "The 2000 rupee note was introduced by the Indian government on November 8, 2016, as part of the demonetization initiative led by Prime Minister Narendra Modi. The primary reasons for introducing this denomination were:\n\n1. To replace the older 1000 rupee note that was demonetized during the currency reform\n\n2. To help facilitate transactions in a cash-dependent economy while introducing higher value currency\n\n3. To reduce the volume of cash in circulation compared to the previous 1000 rupee note\n\n4. To make it easier for people to carry larger amounts of money in fewer notes\n\n5. To potentially discourage black money and counterfeit currency by introducing a new design and security features\n\nHowever, in February 2023, the Reserve Bank of India announced the withdrawal of the 2000 rupee note, stating that it would be gradually phased out from circulation. The note was considered less useful in day-to-day transactions and did not serve its original purpose effectively.\n\nThe introduction and subsequent withdrawal of the 2000 rupee note were part of the government's broader financial and monetary reforms aimed at increasing transparency and reducing unaccounted cash in the economy.",
